pean Parliament|MEP]], denounced him as the [[Antichrist]] and was subjected to booing by fellow MEPs who also threw objects at him;<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/10/12/world/ulster-protestant-interrupts-pope-yelling-antichrist.html | title=Ulster Protestant Interrupts Pope, Yelling 'Antichrist!'  | work=The New York Times | date=12 October 1988 | accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref> [[Otto von Habsburg]] was among those who helped physically eject him from the room.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/politics/paisley-opponent-dies-in-bavaria-1-2835782 | title=Paisley opponent dies in Bavaria  | publisher=Belfast News Letter | date=6 July 2011 | accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Mike Hookem]] punched [[Steven Woolfe]] in the face at a [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] party meeting in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/politics/718281/Ukip-leadership-favourite-Steven-Woolfe-collapses-European-Parliament|title=UKIP's Steven Woolfe rushed to hospital after being 'PUNCHED IN THE FACE' at party meeting|last=Gutteridge|first=Greg Heffer, Political Reporter and Nick|date=2016-10-06|website=Daily Express|access-date=2019-02-07}}</ref>\n\n== Georgia ==\n=== 26 December 2014 ===\nA brawl broke out when an argument over the composition of Georgian delegations in international institutions turned violent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/georgia/11313904/Boxing-Day-brawl-breaks-out-in-Georgian-parliament.html|title=Boxing Day brawl breaks out in Georgian parliament|last=Burke|first=Myles|last2=Dec 2014|first2=video source APTN 5:34PM GMT 26|date=2014-12-26|website=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=2019-02-07}}</ref>\n\n== Greece ==\n\n=== 16 May 2017 ===\nA fight erupted between rival MPs in the [[Hellenic Parliament|Greek Parliament]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/805058/chaos-erupts-Greek-Parliament-fracas-rival-MPs-Ilias-Kasidiaris-golden-dawn-Nikos-Dendias|title='Can't you see I'm talking?' CHAOS in Greek Parliament as fight erupts between rival MPs|last=Nair|first=Ajay|date=2017-05-16|website=Daily Express|access-date=2019-02-07}}</ref>\n\n== Hong Kong ==\nA [[Pro-democracy camp (Hong Kong)|pan-democrat]] lawmaker threw a glass to [[Leung Chun-ying|CY Leung]] before the Legislative meeting and was charged for common assault.\n\nTwo lawmakers who entered the parliament's chamber without being authorized to do so caused a scuffle then the lawmakers tried to read out their oath of office.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/detail/breakingnews/30298957|title=Pro-independence lawmakers brawl in Hong Kong parliament  |work=The Nation|access-date=2017-12-30}}</ref>\n\n== India ==\n\n=== Tamil Nadu ===\nIn January 1988, there was a riot in the [[Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly]] over a vote of majority for [[Janaki Ramachandran]], who was serving as [[Chief Minister (India)|Chief Minister]] following the death in December 1987 of her husband [[MGR]]. The [[ADMK]] party had split, with most [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLAs]] supporting her and some supporting [[Jayalalithaa]]'s bid to become Chief Minister instead. The [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] party with its 60 MLAs was able to play \"kingmaker\".<ref name=\"businessline\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/opinion/columns/rasheeda-bhagat/Pepper-spray-pales-against-past-TN-Assembly-events/article20727766.ece|title=Pepper spray pales against past TN Assembly events|last=Bhagat|first=Rasheeda|website=@businessline|access-date=2019-02-07}}</ref> While the Congress-led Central Government in New Delhi ordered them to vote against Janaki, some Congress MLAs chose to resign instead, allowing the Janaki government to survive the majority vote. A riot ensued in the legislature, with members clubbing each other with microphone stands and footwear, which was finally ended by riot police who stormed the legislature and beat up everybody with their batons.<ref name=\"businessline\" /> The Janaki faction was however dismissed by the Central Government under [[Article 356]] of the Indian Constitution, having survived just 24 days in office. The state was placed under [[President's rule]] for a year, until the next scheduled state assembly elections in January 1989.\n\nOn 25 March 1989, a [[riot]] broke out in the state legislative assembly in [[Tamil Nadu]] between members of the ruling [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam|DMK]] party and the now-unified opposition [[ADMK]] party over the reading of the state budget.<ref name=\"caravan\">[http://www.caravanmagazine.in/vantage/titans-tn-assembly Report]</ref> In the [[melee]], [[Durai Murugan]] tried to disrobe [[J. Jayalalithaa]],<ref name=\"thehindu\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/2003/03/26/stories/2003032605200400.htm|title=The Hindu : 1989 ugly episode haunts the House|website=The Hindu|access-date=2019-02-07}}</ref> [[M. Karunanidhi|Muthuvel Karunanidhi]] had his sunglasses broken,<ref name=\"thehindu\" /> and the budget was torn up by angry rioters.<ref>[http://jagoindian.com/jayalalithaa-chief-minister-of-tamil-nadu/ \"ADMK members tearing the budget report to be read by the ruling party\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021094709/http://jagoindian.com/jayalalithaa-chief-minister-of-tamil-nadu/ |date=2014-10-21 }}</ref>\n\n=== Uttar Pradesh ===\n=== 22 October 1997 ===\nRiots broke out in the state legislative assembly in [[Uttar Pradesh]] with [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLAs]] picking up microphones, chairs, and other items to throw at each other. Security pulled off the tops of desks as a shield for the Speaker.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/19707635.html?FMT=ABS | title=Indian Government Ousts State Leaders | date=1997-10-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Maharashtra ===\n=== 10 November 2009 ===\nA member of the legislative assembly has been assaulted on 10 November 2009 in the state assembly. One of the members 'who can't speak [[Marathi language|Marathi]]' took the oath in [[Hindi]], one of the [[official language]]s of India. This was objected to by a right wing party Maharashtra Navanirmana Samithi, that wants Marathi to be the official language in the state. Four members of the Maharashtra Navaniramana Samithi were immediately suspended for 4 years.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-11-10/india/28082548_1_abu-asim-azmi-oath-taking-vasant-gite |title=MNS lawmakers turn into lawbreakers in Assembly |date=10 November 2009 |work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n== Iran ==\nScuffles broke out in the [[Islamic Consultative Assembly]] after the country's economic and finance minister [[Masoud Karbasian]] was sacked.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-parliament-fight-brawl-finance-economy-minister-masoud-karbasian-a8508811.html Brawl breaks out in Iranian parliament after economic and finance minister is sacked]</ref>\n\n== Iraq ==\nThere has been [[violence]] in the [[Council of Representatives of Iraq]].<ref>[http://english.alarabiya.net/en/2016/04/14/VIDEO-Iraqi-MPs-fight-after-stalled-Cabinet-vote.html Iraqi MPs fight after stalled Cabinet vote]</ref><ref>[http://www.constitutionnet.org/news/op-ed-iraq-constitutional-amendments-face-uphill-battle-amid-parliamentary-dissensus Op-ed: Iraq constitutional amendments face uphill battle amid parliamentary dissensus]</ref>\n\nKurdish MPs brawled in the [[Iraqi Kurdistan Parliament]] over president [[Masoud Barzani]]'s term.<ref>[https://ekurd.net/fight-and-punches-in-iraqi-kurdistan-parliament-over-extending-barzanis-presidency-2015-03-25 Fight and punches in Iraqi Kurdistan parliament over extending Barzani\u2019s presidency]</ref>\n\n== Israel ==\nLegislative violence has happened in Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4016060,00.html|title=Cabinet approves ministerial appointm